    <div class="ing-box"><h4>Postnatal Nutrition: What the Science Says</h4><p>Postpartum nutrition is supported by extensive clinical evidence linking specific nutrient depletions to maternal recovery outcomes and infant development via breast milk.</p><div class="vs-strip">
      <div class="vs-item"><strong>DHA for Postpartum Mood</strong><p>Omega-3 supplementation significantly reduced depressive symptoms in perinatal women in a meta-analysis of multiple RCTs.<br /><em>Translational Psychiatry, 2018</em></p></div>
      <div class="vs-item"><strong>Iron Deficiency Prevalence</strong><p>Up to 50% of postpartum women have iron deficiency, contributing to fatigue, cognitive impairment, and mood disturbance.<br /><em>Am J Obstet Gynecol, 2019</em></p></div>
      <div class="vs-item"><strong>Vitamin D and PPD</strong><p>Vitamin D insufficiency (affecting 70% of postpartum women) is independently associated with higher rates of postpartum depression.<br /><em>Annals General Psychiatry, 2019</em></p></div>
      <div class="vs-item"><strong>Choline for Infant Brain</strong><p>Choline AI increases to 550mg during lactation. It is transferred via breast milk for infant brain development, memory formation, and neural maintenance.<br /><em>Am J Clinical Nutrition, 2018</em></p></div>
