    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Postnatal Gummies</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the difference between prenatal and postnatal vitamins?</summary><p>Prenatals focus on fetal development (folate, iron for blood volume, DHA for fetal brain). Postnatals focus on maternal recovery and breastfeeding — nutrient repletion, DHA for breast milk, mood support, and energy recovery.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Why are postnatal vitamins important for breastfeeding?</summary><p>Breastfeeding transfers nutrients to the infant from maternal stores. Without supplementation, the mother's depleted reserves become further exhausted, contributing to fatigue, bone loss, hair loss, and mood issues.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How long should I take postnatal vitamins?</summary><p>Throughout breastfeeding plus 3-6 months after weaning. Minimum 6 months postpartum. The WHO recommends breastfeeding for at least 2 years.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do postnatal vitamins help with postpartum hair loss?</summary><p>They support the nutritional foundations for hair regrowth — especially iron, biotin, vitamin D, and zinc. While they cannot reverse the hormonal trigger, they ensure follicles have building blocks when they re-enter the growth phase.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can postnatal vitamins help with postpartum mood?</summary><p>DHA, vitamin D, and iron deficiencies are all linked to postpartum mood disturbance. Comprehensive postnatal vitamins address these nutritional risk factors. They are NOT a treatment for PPD — seek professional help for persistent symptoms.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Should postnatal gummies contain DHA?</summary><p>Yes — DHA is critical for infant brain development via breast milk. At least 200-300mg daily is recommended. Algal DHA is preferred for purity.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do I need extra iron after giving birth?</summary><p>Most women do. Total iron cost of pregnancy + delivery is 740-1,040mg. Up to 50% of postpartum women are iron deficient. If your gummy lacks iron, add a separate gentle iron supplement.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are postnatal gummies as effective as pills?</summary><p>For most nutrients, yes. Gummies offer superior compliance for sleep-deprived new mothers. Main limitation: gummies often lack adequate iron, requiring a separate supplement.</p></details>

    <div class="warn-box"><span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span><p><strong>Important:</strong> Postnatal vitamins support recovery and breastfeeding but are not a treatment for postpartum depression, anxiety, or other mood disorders. If you experience persistent low mood, anxiety, intrusive thoughts, or difficulty bonding with your baby, contact your healthcare provider or the Postpartum Support International helpline (1-800-944-4773) immediately. Early intervention is critical.</p></div>

